                <h3>You know the symptoms of dehydration?</h3>
                <p> Dehydration is a potentially serious illness that is characterized by low concentration not only water but also organic minerals and salts in the body fluids, the extent of preventing it to perform its normal functions. The disease may be secondary to acute diarrhea and affect people of all ages but is most dangerous for children (especially newborns and infants) and for the elderly.</p>
                <p><b>Causes</b></p>
                <p>Dehydration occurs if the water eliminated by the body through the breath, sweat, urine, feces and tears is not reset properly. This can happen when fluid intake is insufficient, in cases of vomiting, diarrhea and fever, in hot weather because of excessive sweating in patients with diabetes due to an increase in the number of voids and the uncontrolled use of diuretics .The dehydration can be classified according to the degree of severity as mild, moderate and severe. Are classic signs of mild to moderate dehydration exaggerated thirst, dry mouth and skin, sunken eyes, absence or small tear production, decreased sweating and, in babies, the soft spot sunk. Headache, drowsiness, dizziness, weakness, fatigue and increased heart rate may also be associated with episodes of desidratação.Além these symptoms, which are intensified with the worsening of the picture, in cases of severe dehydration, there may be others like fall blood pressure, unconsciousness, convulsions, coma, organ failure and morte.DiagnósticoO diagnosis of dehydration is based mainly on clinical judgment, but you may need to perform some simple blood tests, stool and urine tests to identify the cause and the severity of the disease.</p>
                <p><b>Treatment</b></p>
                <p>Breast milk is the ideal resource for the treatment of dehydration in the first six months of a child's life. Then, regardless of age, in cases of mild to moderate dehydration, drink plenty of filtered or boiled water in small sips and short breaks can be enough to rehydrate the body. It is important to keep the person in an environment with mild temperatures to prevent water loss by suor.Nos cases of severe dehydration, which can occur from a sudden, rehydration should be done with oral serum distributed free in health centers and available in pharmacies. This serum can be prepared at home and is valid for 24 hours after diluted in water.If is difficult to get the serum for rehydration in health care, it is possible to prepare the ORS, in the following proportions: 1 liter of filtered water or boiled, one level teaspoon salt tea and two level spoons of sugar.</p>
                <p><b>Recommendations</b></p>
                <p>* Drink plenty of fluids, at least two liters a day; <br>
                * Make sure children and the elderly are taking the amount of liquid needed to maintain good hydration of the body. In these age groups, often they forget to do so;
                * Use light clothing and avoid direct exposure to the sun on hot days; <br>
                * Do not practice physical exercises in the hottest hours of the day; <br>
                * Wash your hands before meals and after using the bathroom; <br>
                * Make sure that the foods that will be eaten raw have been properly prepared.</p>
                <p><i>Source: Dr. Varella Varella﻿</i></p>

                <h3>Water is the source of life</h3>
                <p>No matter who we are, what we do, where we live, we depend on it to live. Yet, however great the importance of water, people continue polluting the rivers and its sources, forgetting how much it is essential to our lives.
                <p>Water is probably the only natural resource that has to do with all aspects of human civilization, from the agricultural and industrial development to the cultural values ​​and religious rooted in society. It is an essential natural resource, whether as a biochemical component of living beings as a way of life for many plant and animal species as a representative element of social and cultural values ​​and even as a factor of production of various goods to the end and intermediate consumption.
                <p>According to statistics, 70% of the planet consists of water, and only 3% is fresh water and of this total, 98% is groundwater. This means that most available and safe water is minimal near the total amount of water in our earth. In modern societies, the pursuit of comfort necessarily imply a considerable increase in daily water needs.</p>
                <p>Water resources have profound importance in the development of various economic activities. In relation to agricultural production, water may represent up to 90% of the physical composition of plants. The lack of water in the plant growth periods can destroy crops and to properly deployed ecosystems. In the industry, to obtain various products, the necessary quantities of water are often higher than the volume produced.</p>
                <p>Looking at the data below, we realize that we need to start to use water prudently and rationally, avoiding waste and pollution because:</p>
                <p>- A sixth of the world population, more than one billion people lack access to safe drinking water;</p>
                <p>- 40% of the world population (2,400 million) lack access to basic sanitation services;</p>
                <p>- About 6000 children die every day from diseases related to unsafe water and poor sanitation and hygiene one;</p>
                <p>- According to the UN, by 2025 if current consumption patterns continue, two out of three people worldwide will suffer moderate or severe water shortages.</p>
                <p>Brazil is a privileged country with regard to the amount of water. Has the largest freshwater reserves on Earth, ie 12% of the world total. Its distribution, however, is not uniform across the country. The Amazon, for example, is a region that has the largest river basin in the world. The volume of water of the Amazon River is the largest in the world, being considered an essential river for the planet. At the same time, it is also one of the least populated regions of Brazil.</p>
                <p>In contrast, the largest population concentrations in the country are in the capital, far from the large Brazilian rivers like the Amazon, the São Francisco and the Paraná. The biggest shortage problem is still in the Northeast, where the lack of water for long periods has contributed to the abandonment of the land and migration to urban centers such as Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro, further aggravating the problem of water scarcity these cities.</p>
                <p>In addition, the Brazilian rivers and lakes have been committed by the quality of falling water available for abstraction and treatment. In the Amazon and in the Pantanal, for example, rivers like the Madeira, the Cuiabá and Paraguay already have mercury contamination, metal used in underground mining, and the use of pesticides in crop fields. In large cities, this commitment of quality is caused by discharges of domestic and industrial waste water, and the use of rivers as convenient carriers of waste.﻿</p>

